 triggering the lantern-lattice counterweights.\",\n        \"Recover the cache: forged safety seals, Saltlick glyph ledger scrap, and the memo stamped by Kessa Tharn.\",\n        \"Interview Mira Olt about new crawl-knots and who could tie them so clean.\",\n        \"Convince Thia Mol to share a Lantern signal-trail that leads out toward Saltlick Terraces.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Thia Mol\", \"lines\": \"Look at me, paladin, and listen for the space between my words where the truth keeps its teeth. If I wanted to stop a horn, I would hang a ribbon in the wind and make a prayer of it, and the gale itself would decide whether to hush or to sing. This mess is a clumsy story dressed in my colors, stitched with fear for thread, and it is sized to fit the necks of children who have done nothing but run where bridges do not reach. Someone plants our shadow where the lamplight thins and then charges toll on the panic it buys, because panic is a currency that spends clean and leaves no ledger. I will not answer for that with necks belonging to my children, not while I still have breath to bargain, a grin to mask my fury, and a hundred lanterns that know how to speak to the dark without making it bigger.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Aerin Rell\", \"lines\": \"I don’t want your necks, Thia, and I won’t let anyone weigh them against a rumor and call it justice, not while my oathstone warms near false testimony. I want the hands that tied these knots and pressed these seals, the hands that know which ribs hum loud enough to mask the scrape of a guilty body crawling away. The stamp bears Kessa Tharn’s mark, but the ink is wrong, thin as riverwater and too quick to dry, and the pressure doesn’t speak with her careful, oath-bound weight. And the knots—no street-runner ties this clean on the first try, not with a bite set this precise and a tail tucked to catch a sudden tremor in the chain. What I hear under all of this is a practiced rhythm, a 